scetic traditions at a time when the vitality of other German traditions was disappearing. Power and mastery concerned both Weber and Mann, especially as they tried to resolve problems of politics and culture in Germany. Although their resolutions of the problems they confronted seem inadequate, they show the significance of linking social and political thought to conceptions of self and active worldly practices.Trenchant and illuminating, Goldman's book is essential reading for anyone interested in political theory, social thought, and the intellectual history of Germany.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  a20th century german culture.  a20th century german literature.  aanti-fascism.  aanti-nazi sentiment.  aanti-positivism.  acapitalism.  adisenchantment.  adoctor faustus.  aexilliteratur.  agerman literature.  agerman philosophy.  agermany.  amax weber.  amaximilian karl emil weber.  amodern western society.  amodernity.  apolitical theory.  apolitics as vocation.  apower and mastery.  arationalism.  ascience as vocation.  asecularism.  asocial action.  asocial research.  asocial theory.  asocial thought.  asociology.  athe magic mountain.  athomas mann.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007750840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520912373?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912373423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912373/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles